<% page_title "Helium cookbook" %>

<header class="guide-hero helium-guide-hero">
  <p class="eyebrow">HTML-first interactivity</p>
  <h1>Helium cookbook.</h1>
  <p class="lede">Six small patterns that cover the JavaScript most server-rendered
    apps reach for React, Stimulus, Alpine or Turbo Frames to solve. Hacienda
    keeps the server authoritative; Helium makes the current page feel alive.</p>
</header>

<div class="tutorial-layout full-guide-layout">
  <aside class="tutorial-toc full-guide-toc">
    <strong>Patterns</strong>
    <a href="#filter">01 Product filter</a>
    <a href="#inline-edit">02 Inline edit</a>
    <a href="#modal">03 Modal form</a>
    <a href="#dependent-fields">04 Dependent fields</a>
    <a href="#preview">05 Live preview</a>
    <a href="#pending">06 Pending state</a>
  </aside>

  <article
    class="guide-content helium-cookbook"
    @import="/assets/time_ago.js"
    @init="start_time_ago_clock($data)"
    @data='{
      "timestamp": 0,
      "productQuery": "",
      "stockOnly": false,
      "editingTitle": false,
      "recordTitle": "Blue Monday",
      "draftTitle": "Blue Monday",
      "commentOpen": false,
      "commentBody": "",
      "product_kind": "physical",
      "physical_quantity": 10,
      "digital_downloads": 3,
      "previewBody": "",
      "messageText": ""
    }'
  >
    <section id="filter" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">01 / React-style filtering</span>
      <h2>Filter a product table</h2>
      <p>This is the classic “Thinking in React” product filter. The rows are
        ordinary server-rendered HTML; Helium only owns the local query and checkbox state.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <div class="demo-controls">
          <input type="search" placeholder="Search records…" @bind="productQuery">
          <label class="check-row">
            <input type="checkbox" @bind="stockOnly">
            Only show in-stock items
          </label>
        </div>

        <div class="product-table">
          <article @visible="'factory records tote'.includes(productQuery.toLowerCase()) && (!stockOnly || true)">
            <strong>Factory Records Tote</strong><span>Accessories</span><b>In stock</b>
          </article>
          <article @visible="'unknown pleasures print'.includes(productQuery.toLowerCase()) && (!stockOnly || false)">
            <strong>Unknown Pleasures Print</strong><span>Prints</span><b>Sold out</b>
          </article>
          <article @visible="'hac51 enamel pin'.includes(productQuery.toLowerCase()) && (!stockOnly || true)">
            <strong>HAC51 Enamel Pin</strong><span>Accessories</span><b>In stock</b>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:filter) %></code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="inline-edit" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">02 / Hotwire-style editing</span>
      <h2>Inline edit without a frame</h2>
      <p>Use Helium to swap read/edit states. The save button can still submit a
        normal PATCH form to Hacienda.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <div class="inline-edit-demo" @visible="!editingTitle">
          <h3 id="record-title" @text="recordTitle">Blue Monday</h3>
          <button type="button" @click="editingTitle = true">Edit title</button>
        </div>

        <form
          class="inline-edit-demo"
          method="post"
          action="/records/1"
          @ref="titleForm"
          @visible="editingTitle"
        >
          <input name="title" @bind="draftTitle">
          <button
            @post.prevent="/guides/helium/title-preview"
            @params="new FormData($titleForm)"
            @target="#record-title:replace"
            @click="editingTitle = false"
          >Save title</button>
          <button type="button" @click="editingTitle = false">Cancel</button>
        </form>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:inline_edit) %></code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="modal" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">03 / Modal form</span>
      <h2>Open a modal, submit HTML</h2>
      <p>Helium handles the open/close state. The form remains a plain browser
        submission with CSRF and server validation.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <button type="button" @click="commentOpen = true">New comment</button>
        <dialog class="demo-dialog" :open="commentOpen">
          <form
            method="post"
            action="/comments"
            @ref="commentForm"
          >
            <h3>New comment</h3>
            <textarea name="body" placeholder="Say something useful" @bind="commentBody"></textarea>
            <div class="button-row">
              <button type="button" @click="commentOpen = false">Cancel</button>
              <button
                @post.prevent="/guides/helium/comment-preview"
                @params="new FormData($commentForm)"
                @target="#comment-result:append"
                @click="commentOpen = false, commentBody = ''"
              >Post comment</button>
            </div>
          </form>
        </dialog>
        <div id="comment-result"></div>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:modal) %></code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="dependent-fields" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">04 / Dependent fields</span>
      <h2>Show the fields that matter</h2>
      <p>Common admin-form behaviour does not need a component tree. Bind the
        field that drives the branch and let the server receive normal params.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <label>
          Product type
          <select name="kind" @change="product_kind = $event.target.value">
            <option value="physical">Physical</option>
            <option value="digital">Digital</option>
          </select>
        </label>

        <label @visible="product_kind === 'physical'">
          Stock count
          <input type="number" name="quantity" value="10" @input="physical_quantity = $event.target.value">
        </label>

        <label @visible="product_kind === 'digital'">
          Download limit
          <input type="number" name="download_limit" value="3" @input="digital_downloads = $event.target.value">
        </label>

        <p class="demo-summary">
          <strong @visible="product_kind === 'physical'" @text="physical_quantity + ' physical copies'">10 physical copies</strong>
          <strong @visible="product_kind === 'digital'" @text="digital_downloads + ' downloads per purchase'">3 downloads per purchase</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:dependent_fields) %></code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="preview" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">05 / Live preview</span>
      <h2>Preview text as it is typed</h2>
      <p>This is the kind of small enhancement that often becomes a React island.
        With Helium it stays in the ERB that owns the form.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <textarea name="body" placeholder="Write a post excerpt…" @bind="previewBody"></textarea>
        <aside class="preview-box" @visible="previewBody.length > 0">
          <span class="eyebrow">Preview</span>
          <p @text="previewBody"></p>
        </aside>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:preview) %></code></pre>
    </section>

    <section id="pending" class="cookbook-pattern">
      <span class="step-number">06 / Ajax form feedback</span>
      <h2>Post a form, append an HTML fragment</h2>
      <p>Helium sends ordinary form data to a Hacienda action. The server returns
        HTML and Helium appends it without navigating or replacing earlier messages.</p>

      <div class="demo-card">
        <form
          method="post"
          action="/messages"
          @ref="messageForm"
        >
          <input name="message" placeholder="Message" required @bind="messageText">
          <button
            @post.prevent="/guides/helium/post-preview"
            @params="new FormData($messageForm)"
            @target="#post-result:append"
          >Post message</button>
          <div id="post-result"></div>
        </form>
      </div>

      <pre><code><%= samples.fetch(:pending) %></code></pre>

      <div class="next-guide">
        <p class="eyebrow">The boundary</p>
        <h3>Helium is not the router.</h3>
        <p>Hacienda Navigation handles fast GET page transitions. Native forms
          send writes to the server. Helium covers the local behaviour that makes
          each page feel responsive.</p>
        <%= link "See the TodoMVC example", "https://github.com/hacienda-rb/hacienda/tree/main/examples/todomvc", class: "button button-primary" %>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</div>
